        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <a href="/industries/" class="hover:text-white/70">Industries</a>
        <span class="mx-2">/</span>
        <span class="text-white/70">Warehouse &#x26; Distribution</span>
      </nav>
      <div class="max-w-3xl">
        <div class="section-label text-accent-bright/80 mb-6">Industry</div>
        <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-800 text-white tracking-wide uppercase leading-[0.95] mb-8">
          Warehouse &#x26; Distribution <span class="text-accent-bright">Conveyors</span>
        </h1>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article>
    <section class="py-12 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="aio-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <p id="aio-heading" class="text-lg text-ink leading-relaxed">
          Warehouse and distribution center conveyors move cases, totes, parcels, and pallets through receiving, storage, picking, packing, sortation, and shipping operations. Core conveyor functions include high-speed sortation (routing items to the correct shipping lane), zero-pressure accumulation (staging items without contact pressure), merge (combining multiple flows into one line), and AS/RS integration (connecting automated storage with order fulfillment). Manufacturers like Hytrol, TGW, Dematic, Honeywell Intelligrated, and Interroll supply warehouse conveyor systems from single sections to complete turnkey distribution systems.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SORTATION ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="sort-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Sortation</div>
        <h2 id="sort-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Sortation <span class="text-accent">Conveyors</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Sortation conveyors automatically divert products from a main transport line to designated lanes, chutes, or palletizing stations based on barcode scan, RFID read, or dimensioning data. The sortation system is the throughput bottleneck in most distribution centers , its speed and accuracy determine the facility's maximum order capacity.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Sliding Shoe Sorter</h3>
          <p>
            Sliding shoe sorters use rows of small plastic shoes (diverter elements) mounted on a flat conveyor surface. When an item reaches its designated lane, shoes slide laterally across the belt surface, pushing the item off the main line into the lane. Sliding shoe sorters handle a wide range of package sizes (polybags through cases) at speeds of 300-500+ FPM. They provide gentle handling , no impact or dropping. Hytrol's E24 EZSort and Dematic's sliding shoe platforms are representative systems. <!-- VERIFY: Hytrol E24 EZSort model name -->
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Crossbelt Sorter</h3>
          <p>
            Crossbelt sorters use individual carrier cells, each with a short belt conveyor mounted perpendicular to the direction of travel. When a cell reaches the designated sort point, its belt activates, sliding the item off the cell into the lane. Crossbelt sorters handle the widest range of product types , small polybags, envelopes, cartons, and irregularly shaped items , at 400-600+ FPM. BEUMER Group, Interroll, and Vanderlande supply crossbelt <a href="/conveyor-types/diverting-merging/sortation/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sortation systems</a>.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Pop-Up Wheel Diverter</h3>
          <p>
            Pop-up wheel (or pop-up belt) diverters are embedded in a roller conveyor surface. When activated, wheels or a narrow belt pop up above the roller surface and divert the item at a right angle. Pop-up diverters suit lower-speed applications (100-200 FPM) with moderate sort density (fewer destinations). They are simpler and less expensive than sliding shoe or crossbelt sorters. See <a href="/conveyor-types/transfer-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">transfer conveyors</a> for detailed coverage of right-angle divert technology.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Tilt-Tray Sorter</h3>
          <p>
            Tilt-tray sorters use individual tray carriers that tilt to one side at the sort point, dropping the item into the chute. The tray resets to level for the next load cycle. Tilt-tray sorters handle small, flat items well (apparel, books, small electronics) but struggle with round or irregularly shaped items that roll off the tray prematurely. Speeds: 300-500 FPM.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SORTATION COMPARISON ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="sort-compare-heading">
