                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Technology</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Speed (FPM)</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Product Range</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4 pr-4">Sort Accuracy</th>
                <th class="font-display text-base font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink py-4">Relative Cost</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-base text-ink-muted">
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Sliding shoe</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">300-500+</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Polybags to cases</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">99.5%+</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Crossbelt</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">400-600+</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Widest (polybags to irregulars)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">99.9%+</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Pop-up wheel</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">100-200</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Flat-bottom cases/totes</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">99%+</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Tilt-tray</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">300-500</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Small flat items, apparel</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">99.5%+</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$-$$$$</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ ACCUMULATION & MERGE ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="accum-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Flow Control</div>
        <h2 id="accum-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Accumulation &#x26; <span class="text-accent">Merge Conveyors</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-4">Zero-Pressure Accumulation</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Zero-pressure accumulation conveyors</a> stage products without contact between items. Each zone holds one product and stops independently. When a downstream zone clears, the upstream zone releases its product. This prevents product damage, label scuffing, and case crushing that occurs when products press against each other under back-pressure.
          </p>
          <p>
            <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR (motor-driven roller) conveyors</a> are the standard zero-pressure accumulation technology in modern distribution centers. Each zone contains a motorized roller that drives 3-7 slave rollers through O-ring belts. Photoeye sensors detect product presence and control zone release. MDR zones consume power only when product is present, reducing energy costs by 50-70% compared to continuously running belt conveyors.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-10 mb-4">Merge Conveyors</h3>
          <p>
            Merge conveyors combine flows from multiple pick zones, pack stations, or parallel conveyors onto a single outbound line. The merge must insert items into gaps on the main line without collision or stoppage. Merge technologies:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Speed-up merge:</strong> The merging conveyor accelerates to match the main line speed and inserts items into natural gaps. Simplest and lowest cost. Works when main line has sufficient gap density.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Slug merge:</strong> Holds multiple items on the merge conveyor, then releases them as a group when a gap opens on the main line. Higher throughput than one-at-a-time merging.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Servo-controlled merge:</strong> Servo drives precisely time individual item release to insert into specific gaps on the main line. Highest throughput and most reliable but most expensive.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ AS/RS INTEGRATION ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="asrs-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Automation</div>
        <h2 id="asrs-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          AS/RS &#x26; AMR <span class="text-accent">Integration</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Automated Storage and Retrieval Systems (AS/RS) and Autonomous Mobile Robots (AMRs) connect to the conveyor network through transfer points, staging conveyors, and accumulation zones. The conveyor system is the fixed backbone , AS/RS and AMR systems are the flexible storage and transport layer.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">AS/RS Conveyor Interface</h3>
          <p>
            Conveyors connect to AS/RS cranes and shuttles at the end-of-aisle transfer point. Infeed conveyors deliver loads (cases, totes, pallets) to the AS/RS for storage. Outfeed conveyors receive retrieved loads for picking or shipping. Accumulation zones buffer loads between the conveyor's continuous flow and the AS/RS crane's cycle-based operation. Sizing the accumulation buffer correctly prevents bottlenecks , the buffer must absorb the AS/RS cycle time variation without starving downstream operations.
          </p>
          <p>
            Dematic, TGW, Swisslog, and Honeywell Intelligrated supply integrated AS/RS and conveyor systems. For standalone conveyor systems connecting to third-party AS/RS, the interface specification must define load dimensions, transfer height, conveyor speed, handshake signals, and communication protocol (typically Ethernet/IP or PROFINET).
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">AMR Conveyor Interface</h3>
          <p>
            AMR integration uses conveyor-mounted load/unload stations where AMRs pick up or deliver totes and cases. The station includes a short conveyor section, presence sensors, and a communication interface (Wi-Fi, 5G, or infrared) that coordinates the AMR docking cycle with conveyor motion. AMR providers like 6 River Systems (Shopify), Locus Robotics, and Geek+ integrate with standard conveyor systems through WCS (Warehouse Control System) software.
          </p>
          <!-- VERIFY: 6 River Systems current branding/ownership -->
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ ELEVATION ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="elevation-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Elevation Changes</div>
        <h2 id="elevation-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Vertical Transport in <span class="text-accent">Distribution</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Multi-level distribution centers and mezzanine operations need vertical conveyors to move cases, totes, and pallets between levels. Three technologies serve this need:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Spiral conveyors ($$$):</strong> Continuous-flow spirals move cases and totes through elevation changes without stopping. Compact footprint. Speeds up to 200 FPM. See also: <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/cooling/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">spiral cooling conveyors</a> for food applications.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink"><a href="/conveyor-types/vertical-reciprocating/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Vertical reciprocating conveyors (VRCs)</a> ($$-$$$):</strong> Platform-based lifts that carry cases or pallets between levels. Cycle-based (not continuous). Suited for lower-throughput, heavy-load applications.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Incline/decline belt conveyors ($$):</strong> Belt conveyors at 15-30 degree incline. Simple and low cost for moderate elevation changes. Limited to products that do not slide on the inclined belt surface.</li>
          </ul>
          <p>
            For layout and cost optimization, see the <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> and <a href="/resources/automated-conveyor-systems/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">automated systems guide</a>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>
  </article>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <h2 id="faq-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-800 text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-10">
        Frequently Asked <span class="text-accent">Questions</span>
      </h2>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8" open>
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What conveyors are used in warehouses?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Belt conveyors, <a href="/conveyor-types/roller-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">roller conveyors</a>, sortation (shoe, crossbelt, tilt-tray), <a href="/conveyor-types/accumulation-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">accumulation</a>, merge, and vertical conveyors. <a href="/conveyor-types/mdr-conveyors/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">MDR conveyors</a> are standard for modern zero-pressure accumulation.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is a sortation conveyor?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>A sortation conveyor automatically diverts products to designated lanes based on barcode or RFID data. Types include sliding shoe (gentle, high-speed), crossbelt (widest product range), pop-up wheel (lower-speed), and tilt-tray (small items). Speeds: 100-600+ FPM.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            What is AS/RS conveyor integration?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Conveyors connect AS/RS (Automated Storage/Retrieval Systems) to picking and shipping. Infeed conveyors deliver loads for storage; outfeed conveyors receive retrieved loads. Accumulation zones buffer between continuous conveyor flow and AS/RS cycle timing.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
        <details class="group border border-border bg-surface p-6 open:pb-8">
          <summary class="font-display text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink cursor-pointer list-none flex items-center justify-between group-open:mb-4">
            How do merge conveyors work?
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-ink-muted group-open:rotate-180 transition-transform flex-shrink-0 ml-4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path></svg>
          </summary>
          <div class="text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-3">
            <p>Merge conveyors combine multiple streams into one line using speed-up merges (accelerate into gaps), slug merges (release groups), or servo-controlled merges (precise individual timing). Servo merges provide highest throughput and reliability.</p>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

</baselayout>
